{"title_page": "Dorado barrio-pueblo", "text_new": "{{short description|A municipality seat in Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Dorado barrio-pueblo\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              = <small> Barrio Pueblo Dorado</small>\n| nickname                 = \n| settlement_type          =\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n| image_skyline            =Parroquia San Antonio de Padua de Dorado.jpg\n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = San Antonio de Padua Catholic church in Dorado.\n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = Dorado barrio-pueblo, Dorado, Puerto Rico locator map.png\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico#Caribbean\n| pushpin_map_caption = Dorado barrio-pueblo, Dorado, Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.4592399|-66.261631499999993|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415053|Dorado -Pueblo}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|DoradoFlag.svg}} [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]]<!-- Politics ----------------->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| leader_title1            = \n| leader_name1             =\n| leader_title2            =\n| leader_name2             =\n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n| established_title2       = \n| established_date2        =\n| established_title3       = \n| established_date3        =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi         =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2000 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL ---------->\n| population_total         = 780 \n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW ---->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n| timezone                 =\n| utc_offset               =\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type         =\n| postal_code              =\n| area_code                = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Dorado barrio-pueblo''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] and the administrative center ([[Seat of government|seat]]) of [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]], a municipality of Puerto Rico. Its population in 2010 was 780.<ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref><ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrio-Pueblo\">{{cite web |title=US Census Barrio-Pueblo definition |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/barrio.htm |website=factfinder.com |publisher=US Census |accessdate=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513190743/https://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/barrio.htm |archive-date=13 May 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is one of the 6 [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrios]] in the municipality of [[Dorado, Puerto Rico]], along with Espinosa, Higuillar, Maguayo, Mameyal and R\u00edo Lajas.<ref>[https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2000/phc-3-53-eng.pdf Puerto Rico 2000: Population and Housing Unit Counts]</ref>\n\nAs was customary in Spain, in Puerto Rico, the municipality has a barrio called ''pueblo'' which contains a central plaza, the municipal buildings (city hall), and a Catholic church. [[Fiestas patronales in Puerto Rico|Fiestas patronales]] (patron saint festivals) are held in the central plaza every year.<ref name=\"Santullano\" /><ref name=\"Pariser_5th\">{{cite book |last1=Pariser |first1=Harry S. |title=Explore Puerto Rico, Fifth Edition |date=2003 |publisher=San Francisco: Manatee Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/explorepuertoric0000pari/page/52 52]\u201355 |url=https://archive.org/details/explorepuertoric0000pari |url-access=registration |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhen after the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)]], the U.S. conducted its first census of Puerto Rico, the population of Dorado Pueblo was 937.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n252 161]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==The central plaza history==\nThe central plaza, or square, is a place for official and unofficial recreational events and a place where people can gather and socialize from dusk to dawn. The [[Laws of the Indies]], Spanish law, which regulated life in Puerto Rico in the early 19th century, stated the plaza's purpose was for \"the parties\" (celebrations, festivities) ({{lang-es|a prop\u00f3sito para las fiestas}}), and that the square should be proportionally large enough for the number of neighbors ({{lang-es|grandeza proporcionada al\nn\u00famero de vecinos}}). These Spanish regulations also stated that the streets nearby should be comfortable portals for passersby, protecting them from the elements: sun and rain.<ref name=\"Santullano\">{{cite book|jstor=j.ctvbcd2vs.12|title=Mirada al Caribe|first=Luis A.|last=Santullano|date=10 March 2019|publisher=Colegio de Mexico|volume=54|pages=75\u201378|doi=10.2307/j.ctvbcd2vs.12}}</ref> The San Antonio de Padua Catholic Church in the central plaza was built from the span of 1826 throughout July 1848 with the donated funds of Luis Canales. The earthenware on the floor and the baptistery was donated by Pedro L\u00f3pez Canino and Basilisa Marr\u00e9ro on the year 1909.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pueblo Of Dorado}}\n[[Category:Barrios of Dorado, Puerto Rico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A municipality seat in Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Dorado barrio-pueblo\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              = <small> Barrio Pueblo Dorado</small>\n| nickname                 = \n| settlement_type          =\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n| image_skyline            =Parroquia San Antonio de Padua de Dorado.jpg\n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = San Antonio de Padua Catholic church in Dorado.\n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = Dorado barrio-pueblo, Dorado, Puerto Rico locator map.png\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico#Caribbean\n| pushpin_map_caption = Dorado barrio-pueblo, Dorado, Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.4592399|-66.261631499999993|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415053|Dorado -Pueblo}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|DoradoFlag.svg}} [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]]<!-- Politics ----------------->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| leader_title1            = \n| leader_name1             =\n| leader_title2            =\n| leader_name2             =\n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n| established_title2       = \n| established_date2        =\n| established_title3       = \n| established_date3        =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi         =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2000 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL ---------->\n| population_total         = 780 \n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW ---->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n| timezone                 =\n| utc_offset               =\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = \n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type         =\n| postal_code              =\n| area_code                = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Dorado barrio-pueblo''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] and the administrative center ([[Seat of government|seat]]) of [[Dorado, Puerto Rico|Dorado]], a municipality of Puerto Rico. Its population in 2010 was 780.<ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref><ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrio-Pueblo\">{{cite web |title=US Census Barrio-Pueblo definition |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/barrio.htm |website=factfinder.com |publisher=US Census |accessdate=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513190743/https://factfinder.census.gov/help/en/barrio.htm |archive-date=13 May 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is one of the 6 [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrios]] in the municipality of [[Dorado, Puerto Rico]], along with Espinosa, Higuillar, Maguayo, Mameyal and R\u00edo Lajas.<ref>[https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2000/phc-3-53-eng.pdf Puerto Rico 2000: Population and Housing Unit Counts]</ref>\n\nAs was customary in Spain, in Puerto Rico, the municipality has a barrio called ''pueblo'' which contains a central plaza, the municipal buildings (city hall), and a Catholic church. [[Fiestas patronales in Puerto Rico|Fiestas patronales]] (patron saint festivals) are held in the central plaza every year.<ref name=\"Santullano\" /><ref name=\"Pariser_5th\">{{cite book |last1=Pariser |first1=Harry S. |title=Explore Puerto Rico, Fifth Edition |date=2003 |publisher=San Francisco: Manatee Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/explorepuertoric0000pari/page/52 52]\u201355 |url=https://archive.org/details/explorepuertoric0000pari |url-access=registration |accessdate=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWhen after the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)]], the U.S. conducted its first census of Puerto Rico, the population of Dorado Pueblo was 937.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n252 161]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==The central plaza history==\nThe central plaza, or square, is a place for official and unofficial recreational events and a place where people can gather and socialize from dusk to dawn. The [[Laws of the Indies]], Spanish law, which regulated life in Puerto Rico in the early 19th century, stated the plaza's purpose was for \"the parties\" (celebrations, festivities) ({{lang-es|a prop\u00f3sito para las fiestas}}), and that the square should be proportionally large enough for the number of neighbors ({{lang-es|grandeza proporcionada al\nn\u00famero de vecinos}}). These Spanish regulations also stated that the streets nearby should be comfortable portals for passersby, protecting them from the elements: sun and rain.<ref name=\"Santullano\">{{cite book|jstor=j.ctvbcd2vs.12|title=Mirada al Caribe|first=Luis A.|last=Santullano|date=10 March 2019|publisher=Colegio de Mexico|volume=54|pages=75\u201378|doi=10.2307/j.ctvbcd2vs.12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pueblo Of Dorado}}\n[[Category:Barrios of Dorado, Puerto Rico]]\n", "name_user": "Ianpavlo", "label": "safe", "comment": "The San Antonio de Padua Catholic Church history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorado_barrio-pueblo"}
{"title_page": "Novelty (1863 ship)", "text_new": "''Novelty'' was a [[schooner]]-rigged iron [[paddle steamer]], built at [[Sydney]] in 1863.\n\n== Construction ==\n''Novelty'' was built in 1863 by [https://dictionaryofsydney.org/organisation/pn_russell_co P.N. Russell and Company], the Sydney [[foundry]] owned and operated by the Australian engineer [[Peter Nicol Russell]].  Its length was 82.5 ft, beam 15.5 ft, depth 5.3 ft.\n\n== Voyages ==\nFrom the date of launching, the vessel made numerous voyages between Australia and New Zealand, carrying passengers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZ18630506.2.6?end_date=31-12-1889&items_per_page=100&query=novelty+ship&snippet=true&start_date=01-01-1863|title=NEW ZEALANDER, VOLUME XIX, ISSUE 1863, 6 MAY 1863|last=|first=|date=|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> and cargo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/CHP18720203.2.5?end_date=31-12-1889&items_per_page=100&query=novelty+ship&snippet=true&start_date=01-01-1863|title=PRESS, VOLUME XIX, ISSUE 2733, 3 FEBRUARY 1872|last=|first=|date=|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>.\n\n== Wreck ==\n''Novelty'' was wrecked off [[Quail Island (New Zealand)|Quail Island]], [[Lyttelton Harbour]], in 1887.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ingram & Wheatley|first=C.W. & P.O.|title=New Zealand Shipwrecks|publisher=Hodder Moa|year=2007|isbn=978-1-86971-093-4|location=Auckland|pages=263}}</ref>\n\nThere are no known remains of ''Novelty'' to show where it sank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmaritime.co.nz/|title=The New Zealand Maritime Record|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "''Novelty'' was a [[schooner]]-rigged iron [[paddle steamer]], built at [[Sydney]] in 1863.\n\n== Construction ==\n''Novelty'' was built in 1863 by [https://dictionaryofsydney.org/organisation/pn_russell_co P.N. Russell and Company], the Sydney [[foundry]] owned and operated by the Australian engineer [[Peter Nicol Russell]].  Its length was 82.5 ft, beam 15.5 ft, depth 5.3 ft.\n\n== Voyages ==\nFrom the date of launching, the vessel made numerous voyages between Australia and New Zealand, carrying passengers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZ18630506.2.6?end_date=31-12-1889&items_per_page=100&query=novelty+ship&snippet=true&start_date=01-01-1863|title=NEW ZEALANDER, VOLUME XIX, ISSUE 1863, 6 MAY 1863|last=|first=|date=|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> and cargo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/CHP18720203.2.5?end_date=31-12-1889&items_per_page=100&query=novelty+ship&snippet=true&start_date=01-01-1863|title=PRESS, VOLUME XIX, ISSUE 2733, 3 FEBRUARY 1872|last=|first=|date=|website=paperspast.natlib.govt.nz|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>.\n\n== Wreck ==\n''Novelty'' was wrecked off [[Quail Island (New Zealand)|Quail Island]], [[Lyttelton Harbour]], in 1887.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Ingram & Wheatley|first=C.W. & P.O.|title=New Zealand Shipwrecks|publisher=Hodder Moa|year=2007|isbn=978-1-86971-093-4|location=Auckland|pages=263}}</ref>\n\nThere are no known remains of ''Novelty'' to show where it sank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nzmaritime.co.nz/|title=The New Zealand Maritime Record|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added {{Uncategorized}} tag to article (UsingTwinkle)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Novelty_(1863_ship)"}
{"title_page": "Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford of Heytesbury}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n[[File:Sir Walter Hungerford, monument.jpg|thumb|18th c. drawing of [[ledger stone]] from lost monument of Sir Walter Hungerford in the North nave of Salisbury Cathedral. Only the [[matrix|matrices]] remain to show the form of the looted [[monumental brass]]es, of which many were ''Hungerford Sickles'', his heraldic badge]]\n[[File:Seal WalterHungerford 1stBaronHungerford KG Died1449.png|thumb|Post 1418<ref>In Nov 1418 he was granted the Barony of Homet in Normandy, office insribed on seal</ref> seal of Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford. Latin inscription: ''SIGILLU(M WALTERI DE HUN)GERFORD DOM(INI) DE HEYTESBURY + DE HOMET'' (\"Seal of Walter de Hungerford, lord of Heytesbury and of Homet\"). His arms of Hungerford are shown on a shield couch\u00e9e, centre, supported by two Hungerford [[sickle]]s. His crest is the Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garb]] between two Hungerford sickles. The banner at [[Dexter and sinister|dexter]] shows ''Party per pale indented  gules and vert, a chevron or'' (de Heytesbury)<ref>Footnote from Britton, John, History and Antiquities of Bath Abbey Church, London, 1825, p.47</ref> and at [[Dexter and sinister|sinister]] ''Barry of six ermine and gules'' (Hussey, his mother's family)]]\n[[File:WalterHungerford 1stBaronHungerford GarterStallPlate WindsorCastle.jpg|thumb|200px|''Le Sire de H(u)ng(er)forde, Waulter''. [[Garter stall plate]], [[Windsor Castle]], of Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford, KG. The helm is covered by mantling ''barry of ermine and gules'', the arms of Hussey. The crest is: ''Within a crest coronet azure a Peverell garb or between two Hungerford sickles argent'']]\n\n'''Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford''' [[Order of the Garter|KG]] (1378\u20139 August 1449) was an English [[knight]] and [[Landed gentry|landowner]], from 1400 to 1414 Member of the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]], of which he became [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker]], then was an [[Admiral]] and [[Peerage of England|peer]].\n\nHe won renown in the [[Hundred Years' War]], fighting in many engagements, including the [[Battle of Agincourt]] in 1415. He was an English envoy at the [[Council of Constance]] in 1415. In 1417 he was made [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|admiral of the fleet]]. On the death of [[Henry V of England|Henry V]] he was an executor of Henry's will and a member of [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Protector Gloucester]]'s council. He attended the [[Congress of Arras|conference at Arras]] in 1435, and was a Member of the [[House of Lords]] sitting as [[Baron Hungerford]] from January 1436 until his death in 1449. From 1426 to 1432, he served as [[Lord High Treasurer]]. Hungerford's tenure as Treasurer occurred during the [[Great Bullion Famine]] and the beginning of the [[Great Slump (15th century)|Great Slump in England]].\n\n==Origins==\nHe was the only surviving son and heir of Sir [[Thomas Hungerford (Speaker)|Thomas Hungerford]] (died 1398) of [[Farleigh Castle]] in Wiltshire,{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}} the first person to be recorded in the rolls of the [[Parliament of England]] as holding the office of [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]].<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=43659&strquery=thomas%20hungerford Journal of the House of Commons: January 1559] at British History Online</ref> His mother was his father's second wife, Joan Hussey (died 1412), daughter and heiress of Sir Edmund Hussey of Holbrook.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}}\n\n==Career==\nHis father had been strongly attached to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] cause at the close of the reign of King Richard II (1377\u20131399), having been steward in the household of [[John of Gaunt]]. On the accession of King Henry IV in 1399, Walter was knighted and was granted an annuity of \u00a340 out of the lands of Margaret, Duchess of Norfolk.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}} He served as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wiltshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire]] in October 1400, in 1404, 1407, 1413, and in January 1413\u201314, and served as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Somerset (UK Parliament constituency)|Somerset]] in 1409. He served as [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]] from 29 January 1413/14, the last parliament in which he served as an MP.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Manning, ''Lives of the Speakers'', p. 55.</ref>\n\nHe was appointed [[Sheriff of Wiltshire]] for 1405, during which term he pronounced his own selection as MP for Wiltshire, and as [[Sheriff of Somerset and Dorset]] for 1414.{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}}\n\nHungerford won renown as a warrior. In 1401 he was with the English army in France, and is said to have defeated the French king in a duel outside Calais. He distinguished himself in battle and tournament, and received substantial rewards. In consideration of his services he was granted in 1403 one hundred marks per annum, payable by the town and castle of [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]] in Wiltshire, and was appointed Sheriff of Wiltshire. On 22 July 1414 he was nominated ambassador to treat for a league with Sigismund, King of the Romans,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 186</ref> and as the English envoy attended the [[Council of Constance]] in 1414\u201315.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: [[cf.]] his accounts of expenses in ''Brit. Mus. Addit. MS''. 24513, f. 68.</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 1415, with twenty men-at-arms and sixty horse archers, Hungerford accompanied King Henry V to France.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Nicolas, ''Agincourt'', p. 381</ref> He can probably be identified correctly as the officer who on the eve of the [[Battle of Agincourt]] expressed regret that the English had not ten thousand archers, which drew a famous rebuke from the king. In Shakespeare's ''Henry V,'' however, this officer is the Earl of Westmoreland.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Nicolas, ''Agincourt'' pp. 105, 241.</ref> He fought bravely at the Battle of Agincourt, but the legend that he took [[Charles, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]] prisoner is not substantiated. He was employed in May 1416 in diplomatic negotiations with ambassadors of Theodoric, [[Archbishop of Cologne]]<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 158.</ref> and in November 1417 with envoys from France.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 25.</ref>\n\nIn 1417 he was made [[Admiral of the Fleet]] under [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]], and in 1418 was with King Henry V at the [[Siege of Rouen]]. In November 1418 he was designated [[Lord Steward|Steward of the King's Household]],<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. iii. p. 76.</ref> and was granted the barony of Hommet in Normandy (today [[Le Hommet-d'Arthenay|Le Hommet]]). He took part in the peace negotiations of 1419 and on 3 May 1421 was installed as a [[Knight of the Garter]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Beltz, ''Hist. of Garter'', p. clviii.</ref>\n\nHungerford was an executor of the will of King Henry V, and in 1422 became a member of the council of the [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester]], the [[Lord Protector]]. In 1424 he was made [[Steward of the Household]] of the infant King Henry VI, and on 7 January 1425/6 was summoned by [[writ]] to Parliament as [[Baron Hungerford]]. The summons was continued to him until his death. Hungerford became [[Treasurer of England]] in succession to Bishop Stafford, when Bishop Beaufort's resignation of the [[Great Seal of the Realm|Great Seal]] in March 1426-7 placed Gloucester in supreme power. He acted as Carver at Henry VI's coronation in Paris in December 1430,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Waurin, ''Chron''., Rolls Ser.,iv. 11</ref> but on the change of ministry which followed Henry VI's return from France in February 1431\u20132, he ceased to be Treasurer. He attended the [[Congress of Arras|conference at Arras]] in 1435.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: ''Wars of Henry VI in France'', Rolls Ser., ed. Stevenson, ii. 431.</ref>\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\n[[File:Arms Peverell OfSampfordPeverell Devon.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of Peverell of [[Sampford Peverell]], Devon: ''Azure, three garbs argent a chief or''<ref>Pole, p.496</ref>]]\n[[File:HungerfordKnot.png|thumb|200px|The marriage of Sir Walter Hungerford to Catherine Peverell is symbolised in a heraldic badge showing the [[Hungerford knot]] uniting the Hungerford [[sickle]] and the Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garb]], the latter a badge of the ancient Peverel family, [[Honour of Peverel|feudal barons of Peverel]] (or of \"the Peak\") in [[Derbyshire]]]]\nHungerford married twice:\n* Firstly to Catherine (or Eleanor) Peverell, daughter of Sir Thomas Peverell, MP, of Parke and Hamatethy, Cornwall{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}} (a cadet branch of Peverell of [[Sampford Peverell]] in Devon<ref>Pole, p.227 re descent of manor of Wolmerston</ref>) by his wife Margaret Courtenay (1355\u20131422{{citation needed|date=September 2013|reason=for the dates}}) one of the two daughters and eventual sole heiresses of Sir [[Thomas Courtenay (of Wootton Courtenay)|Thomas Courtenay]] (died 1356)<ref>Date of birth \"1315 or before\" ({{harvnb|Knight|2016}} cites {{harvnb|Richardson|''Magna Carta Ancestry''}}; death date  \"1356\" ({{harvnb|Knight|2016}} cites {{harv|Richardson|''Magna Carta Ancestry''}}; and & {{harvnb|Vivian|1895|p=244}}</ref> of [[Wootton Courtenay]] in Somerset and of Woodhuish, Devon,{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}} by whom he had three sons and at least one daughter:\n** Walter Hungerford, eldest son and [[heir apparent]], who was made a [[prisoner of war]] in France in 1425, was ransomed by his father for three thousand marks, was in the [[retinue]] of [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]] in France in 1435, and predeceased his father without issue.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n** [[Robert Hungerford, 2nd Baron Hungerford]], eldest surviving son and heir.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n** Edmund Hungerford, who was knighted by Henry VI after the [[Battle of Verneuil]] on Whit-Sunday 1426,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites: Metcalfe, ''Book of Knights'', p.1</ref> and married Margaret Burnell, daughter and co-heiress of Edward Burnell, by whom he had two sons:\n*** Thomas Hungerford, ancestor of the Hungerfords of [[Down Ampney]] in Gloucestershire, of the Hungerfords of [[Windrush, Oxfordshire]] and of the Hungerfords of [[Black Bourton]], Oxfordshire.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n*** Edward Hungerford, ancestor of the Hungerfords of [[Foxham, Wiltshire|Cadenham]], Wiltshire.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}[[File:BishopBishopPeterCourtenay ChimneypieceExeterPalace SeeImpalingCourtenay.JPG|thumb|200px|Arms of Bishop [[Peter Courtenay]] (d.1492), showing the arms of the [[See of Exeter]] impaling Courtenay of Powderham, incorporating [[Badge (heraldry)|heraldic badges]] of [[dolphin]]s of Courtenay of Powderham and in the [[spandrel]]s, Hungerford [[sickle]]s and Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garbs]]. Detail from the Courtenay Mantelpiece, Bishop's Palace, Exeter]]\n** Elizabeth Hungerford (died 14 December 1476), who married Sir [[Philip Courtenay (died 1463)|Philip Courtenay]] (1404\u20131463) of [[Manor of Powderham|Powderham]], Devon.{{sfn|Vivian|1895|p=246}} On her marriage she took to her husband as her [[marriage portion]] the [[manor of Molland]] in North Devon, which she gave to her second son Sir Philip Courtenay of Molland (died 1488), who founded a junior branch of the Courtenay family there.{{sfn|Vivian|1895|p=246, 251-225}} A fragment of an ancient [[chest tomb]] in Molland Church displays heraldic motifs of two interlaced Hungerford sickles and a dolphin of Courtenay of Powderham. Her third son was [[Peter Courtenay]] (c.1432\u20131492) [[Bishop of Exeter]] and [[Bishop of Winchester]], whose splendid surviving mantlepiece in the [[Bishop's Palace, Exeter]] displays much heraldry including Hungerford sickles and Peverell garbs.<ref>A Delineation of the Courtenay Mantelpiece in the Episcopal Palace at Exeter by Roscoe Gibbs with a Biographical Notice of The Right Reverend Peter Courtenay, DD,... To which is added A Description of the Courtenay Mantelpiece compiled by Maria Halliday, privately published at the Office of the Torquay Directory, 1884, p.10</ref>\n* Secondly he married Eleanor Berkeley (died 1 August 1455), daughter of [[John Berkeley (1352\u20131428)|Sir John Berkeley]] of [[Beverstone Castle]], Gloucestershire,{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}} (by his second wife, Elizabeth Betteshorne).<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/berkeley-sir-john-i-1352-1428|title=BERKELEY, Sir John I (1352-1428), of Beverstone castle, Glos. - History of Parliament Online|website=www.historyofparliamentonline.org}}</ref> Eleanor Berkeley was a widow successively of [[John FitzAlan, 13th Earl of Arundel]] (died 1421) and of Sir Richard Poynings (died 1429){{sfn|Richardson II|2011|p=428}}{{sfn|Richardson III|2011|pp=394\u20135}}).<ref name=\"parliament\"></ref> Walter Hungerford and Eleanor de Berkeley were without progeny.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nHungerford died on 9 August 1449 and was buried beside his first wife in [[Salisbury Cathedral]], where two beautiful mortuary chapels erected by the Hungerford family stood until removed and destroyed by the restorations of [[James Wyatt]] in 1790. [[William Henry Hamilton Rogers|William Hamilton Rogers]] (1877) wrote as follows concerning the monument:{{sfn|Rogers|1877|p=184}}{{sfn|Lee|1891|pp=258\u2013259}}\n:\"He was buried with his wife in the Hungerford Chapel in the nave, a beautiful structure composed chiefly of iron and which has since been removed to the choir. Their tombs, joined together and despoiled of their brass effigies, remain in the nave. The matrices exhibit the proportions of a knight on the one and of a lady on the other, both stones were powdered over with sickles and a [[ledger line]] outside all. The whole has now disappeared, except the stones in which the brasses were set. Forty shields of arms, according to Hutchins (who minutely describes these chapels previous to their removal) were set round outside exhibiting the various alliances of the family. Among these were Hungerford impaling Strange and Mohun, Peverell, Courtenay, St John, Mules, etc\".{{efn|The heraldry was also described at length by [[Richard Symonds (diarist)|Richard Symonds]] in his ''Diary of the Marches of the Royal Army'', (1644).{{sfn|Symonds|Roy|Long|1859|pp=137\u2013140}}}}\n\n==Benefactions==\nBy his marriages and royal grants Hungerford added largely to the family estates. He built chantries at [[Church of St Peter and St Paul, Heytesbury|Heytesbury]] and [[St Andrew's Church, Chippenham|Chippenham]], and made bequests to [[Salisbury Cathedral]] and to [[Bath Cathedral]]. In 1428 he presented valuable estates to the [[St Stephen's Chapel|Royal Chapel]] in the [[Palace of Westminster]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites: Jackson, ''Anc. Statutes of Heytesbury Almshouses'', Devizes, 1863.</ref> He founded an [[almshouse]] in 1442<ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.wiltshire.gov.uk/community/getcom.php?id=115|title=Heytesbury|website=Wiltshire Community History|publisher=Wiltshire Council|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> at [[Heytesbury]] for twelve poor men and one woman, with a schoolmaster's residence; after being re-endowed by Margaret de Botreaux, widow of his son Robert, and then rebuilt in 1769 after a fire, the charity continues today as the Hospital of St John.<ref>{{cite web|website=British History Online|title=Victoria County History: Wiltshire: Vol 3 pp337-340 \u2013 Hospitals: St John and St Katherine, Heytesbury|editor-first1=R.B.|editor-last1=Pugh|editor-first2=Elizabeth|editor-last2=Crittall|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/wilts/vol3/pp337-340|publisher=University of London|accessdate=24 March 2017|date=1956}}</ref><ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1284088|desc=Hospital of St. John|access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his will he left to his daughter-in-law, Margaret de Botreaux (wife of Sir Robert Hungerford, 2nd Baron), his \"best legend of the Lives of the Saints\" and to John, Viscount Beaumont he bequeathed a cup formerly used by [[John of Gaunt]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites [[Nicholas Harris Nicolas]]'s ''Testamenta Vetusta'', pp.&nbsp;257\u20139</ref>\n\nIn 1407 Hungerford donated the [[advowson]] of the church at his manor of [[Rushall, Wiltshire|Rushall]] in Wiltshire to the [[Canons regular|canons]] of [[Longleat Priory]], who were struggling to support themselves financially.{{sfn|Pugh|Crittall|1956|p=302\u2013303}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web |last=Knight |first=Patrick |date=September 2016 |url=http://www.knight-france.com/geneal/names/3942.htm |title=Sir Thomas DE COURTENAY, Knt., Of Woodhuish & Dunterton & ... [3942] |publisher= Genealogy - KNIGHTs from Continental Europe to England/Ireland, to Philadelphia (PA), to France |ref=harv |accessdate=3 December 2016}}<!-- This is not a reliable source, but its source is so can be used with [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]-->\n*{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |editor-last=Everingham|editor-first=Kimball G.|title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |publisher=Genealogical Pub. Co.|year=2005|ref={{sfnRef|Richardson|Magna Carta Ancestry}}|edition=2nd}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pole |first=Sir William |authorlink=William Pole (antiquary) |title=Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon |editor-last=Pole |editor-first= Sir John-William de la |editor-link=Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet |location=London |year=1791 |page=496}}\n*{{Cite book  |editor1-last=Pugh |editor1-first=R.B. |editor2-last=Crittall |editor2-first=Elizabeth |year=1956 |chapter=Houses of Augustinian canons: Priory of Longleat |title=A History of the County of Wiltshire |volume=3 |pages=302\u2013303 |chapter-url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=36541 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |year=2011 |title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |edition=2nd  |editor-last=Everingham |editor-first=Kimball G.|volume=II |location=Salt Lake City |isbn=978-1449966386 |ref={{sfnref |Richardson II |2011}} }}\n*{{Cite book  |last=Richardson |first=Douglas  |year=2011 |title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |edition=2nd |editor-last=Everingham |editor-first=Kimball G. |volume=III |location=Salt Lake City |isbn=978-1449966393 |ref={{sfnref |Richardson III |2011}} }}\n*{{cite book |last=Rogers |first=William Henry Hamilton |author-link=William Henry Hamilton Rogers |title=The Antient Sepulchral Effigies and Monumental and Memorial Sculpture of Devon |location=Exeter |year=1877 |page=184 |url=http://www.mocavo.co.uk/The-Ancient-Sepulchral-Effigies-and-Monumental-and-Memorial-Sculpture-of-Devon-2/392542/257 |ref=harv |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225043753/http://www.mocavo.co.uk/The-Ancient-Sepulchral-Effigies-and-Monumental-and-Memorial-Sculpture-of-Devon-2/392542/257 |archivedate=25 February 2015}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Roskell |first1=J. S. |last2=Kightly |first2=Charles |year=1993 |chapter=Hungerford, Sir Walter (1378\u20131449), of Farleigh Hungerford, Som. and Heytesbury, Wilts. |title=The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1386\u20131421 |editor1-last=Roskell |editor1-first=J.S. |editor2-last=Clark |editor2-first=L. |editor3-last=Rawcliffe |editor3-first=C. |publisher=Boydell and Brewer |chapter-url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/hungerford-sir-walter-1378-1449 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Vivian |editor-first=John Lambrickn |editor-link=John Lambrick Vivian |year=1895 |chapter=Pedigree of Courtenay |title=The Visitations of the County of Devon: Comprising the Heralds' Visitations of 1531, 1564 & 1620 |location=Exeter |page=246 |ref=harv|title-link=Heraldic visitation }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Symonds |first1=Richard |last2=Roy |first2=Ian |last3=Long |first3=C. E. |title=Richard Symonds's Diary of the Marches of the Royal Army |year=1859  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kLhWCHRp8foC&pg=PA138 |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-62656-9 |pages=137\u2013140 |ref=harv}}\n\n;Attribution\n* {{DNB|first=Sidney|last=Lee|wstitle=Hungerford, Walter (d.1449)|volume=28|pages=258, 259}}\n** Dugdale's Baronage; Burke's Extinct Peerage;\n** Collinson's Somerset, iii. 354;\n** Hoare's Hungerfordiana, 1823;\n** Maclean's Trigg Minor, i. 358 sq.;\n** Hoare's Mod. Wiltshire, Heytesbury Hundred;\n** Kymer's Fcedera;\n** Stubbs's Const. Hist.;\n** Nicolas's Battle of Agincourt, 1832;\n** Monstrelet's Chroniques, ed. Doiiet d'Arcq (Soc. de 1'Hist. de France), 1862, ii. 404, iv. 93, vi. 314;\n** Manning's Lives of the Speakers.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Goddard, Edward Hungerford (editor 1869). ''The Wiltshire arch\u00e6ological and natural history magazine, Volumes 11\u201312'', Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Society, H. Bull. [https://books.google.com/books?id=orEUAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA154&ots=ZLMFuzEPAx&pg=PA154#v=onepage&f=false p. 154]\n* Burke, Bernard (1866). ''A genealogical history of the dormant, abeyant, forfeited, and extinct peerages of the British empire'', Harrison [https://books.google.com/books?id=1ysWkXKSrpIC&lpg=PA291&ots=K7nMQxJjaL&pg=PA291#v=onepage&f=false p. 291]\n* [[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Hoare, Sir Richard Colt, 2nd Baronet]] (d.1838), ''Hungerfordiana or, The Memoirs of the Family of Hungerford'', 1823\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box |title=[[Speaker of the British House of Commons|Speaker of the House of Commons]] |before=[[John Doreward]] |after=[[Thomas Chaucer]]| years=1414\u20131415}}\n{{Succession box |title=[[Lord High Treasurer]] |before=[[John Stafford (archbishop)|John Stafford]] |after=[[John Scrope, 4th Baron Scrope of Masham|The Lord Scrope of Masham]]| years=1426\u20131432}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{House of Lancaster Lord High Treasurers}}\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hungerford, Walter}}\n[[Category:1378 births]]\n[[Category:1449 deaths]]\n[[Category:English MPs February 1413]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1407]]\n[[Category:English admirals]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Dorset]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Somerset]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Hungerford family|Walter]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Lord High Treasurers of England]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Commons of England]]\n[[Category:English MPs November 1414]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1415]]\n[[Category:Barons Hungerford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford of Heytesbury}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n[[File:Sir Walter Hungerford, monument.jpg|thumb|18th c. drawing of [[ledger stone]] from lost monument of Sir Walter Hungerford in the North nave of Salisbury Cathedral. Only the [[matrix|matrices]] remain to show the form of the looted [[monumental brass]]es, of which many were ''Hungerford Sickles'', his heraldic badge]]\n[[File:Seal WalterHungerford 1stBaronHungerford KG Died1449.png|thumb|Post 1418<ref>In Nov 1418 he was granted the Barony of Homet in Normandy, office insribed on seal</ref> seal of Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford. Latin inscription: ''SIGILLU(M WALTERI DE HUN)GERFORD DOM(INI) DE HEYTESBURY + DE HOMET'' (\"Seal of Walter de Hungerford, lord of Heytesbury and of Homet\"). His arms of Hungerford are shown on a shield couch\u00e9e, centre, supported by two Hungerford [[sickle]]s. His crest is the Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garb]] between two Hungerford sickles. The banner at [[Dexter and sinister|dexter]] shows ''Party per pale indented  gules and vert, a chevron or'' (de Heytesbury)<ref>Footnote from Britton, John, History and Antiquities of Bath Abbey Church, London, 1825, p.47</ref> and at [[Dexter and sinister|sinister]] ''Barry of six ermine and gules'' (Hussey, his mother's family)]]\n[[File:WalterHungerford 1stBaronHungerford GarterStallPlate WindsorCastle.jpg|thumb|200px|''Le Sire de H(u)ng(er)forde, Waulter''. [[Garter stall plate]], [[Windsor Castle]], of Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford, KG. The helm is covered by mantling ''barry of ermine and gules'', the arms of Hussey. The crest is: ''Within a crest coronet azure a Peverell garb or between two Hungerford sickles argent'']]\n\n'''Walter Hungerford, 1st Baron Hungerford''' [[Order of the Garter|KG]] (1378\u20139 August 1449) was an English [[knight]] and [[Landed gentry|landowner]], from 1400 to 1414 Member of the [[House of Commons of England|House of Commons]], of which he became [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker]], then was an [[Admiral]] and [[Peerage of England|peer]].\n\nHe won renown in the [[Hundred Years' War]], fighting in many engagements, including the [[Battle of Agincourt]] in 1415. He was an English envoy at the [[Council of Constance]] in 1415. In 1417 he was made [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|admiral of the fleet]]. On the death of [[Henry V of England|Henry V]] he was an executor of Henry's will and a member of [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester|Protector Gloucester]]'s council. He attended the [[Congress of Arras|conference at Arras]] in 1435, and was a Member of the [[House of Lords]] sitting as [[Baron Hungerford]] from January 1436 until his death in 1449. From 1426 to 1432, he served as [[Lord High Treasurer]]. Hungerford's tenure as Treasurer occurred during the [[Great Bullion Famine]] and the beginning of the [[Great Slump (15th century)|Great Slump in England]].\n\n==Origins==\nHe was the only surviving son and heir of Sir [[Thomas Hungerford (Speaker)|Thomas Hungerford]] (died 1398) of [[Farleigh Castle]] in Wiltshire,{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}} the first person to be recorded in the rolls of the [[Parliament of England]] as holding the office of [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]].<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=43659&strquery=thomas%20hungerford Journal of the House of Commons: January 1559] at British History Online</ref> His mother was his father's second wife, Joan Hussey (died 1412), daughter and heiress of Sir Edmund Hussey of Holbrook.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}}\n\n==Career==\nHis father had been strongly attached to the [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] cause at the close of the reign of King Richard II (1377\u20131399), having been steward in the household of [[John of Gaunt]]. On the accession of King Henry IV in 1399, Walter was knighted and was granted an annuity of \u00a340 out of the lands of Margaret, Duchess of Norfolk.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=258}} He served as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wiltshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Wiltshire]] in October 1400, in 1404, 1407, 1413, and in January 1413\u201314, and served as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Somerset (UK Parliament constituency)|Somerset]] in 1409. He served as [[List of Speakers of the House of Commons of England|Speaker of the House of Commons]] from 29 January 1413/14, the last parliament in which he served as an MP.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Manning, ''Lives of the Speakers'', p. 55.</ref>\n\nHe was appointed [[Sheriff of Wiltshire]] for 1405, during which term he pronounced his own selection as MP for Wiltshire, and as [[Sheriff of Somerset and Dorset]] for 1414.{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}}\n\nHungerford won renown as a warrior. In 1401 he was with the English army in France, and is said to have defeated the French king in a duel outside Calais. He distinguished himself in battle and tournament, and received substantial rewards. In consideration of his services he was granted in 1403 one hundred marks per annum, payable by the town and castle of [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]] in Wiltshire, and was appointed Sheriff of Wiltshire. On 22 July 1414 he was nominated ambassador to treat for a league with Sigismund, King of the Romans,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 186</ref> and as the English envoy attended the [[Council of Constance]] in 1414-15.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: [[cf.]] his accounts of expenses in ''Brit. Mus. Addit. MS''. 24513, f. 68.</ref>\n\nIn the autumn of 1415, with twenty men-at-arms and sixty horse archers, Hungerford accompanied King Henry V to France.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Nicolas, ''Agincourt'', p. 381</ref> He can probably be identified correctly as the officer who on the eve of the [[Battle of Agincourt]] expressed regret that the English had not ten thousand archers, which drew a famous rebuke from the king. In Shakespeare's ''Henry V,'' however, this officer is the Earl of Westmoreland.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Nicolas, ''Agincourt'' pp. 105, 241.</ref> He fought bravely at the Battle of Agincourt, but the legend that he took [[Charles, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans]] prisoner is not substantiated. He was employed in May 1416 in diplomatic negotiations with ambassadors of Theodoric, [[Archbishop of Cologne]]<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 158.</ref> and in November 1417 with envoys from France.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. ii. p. 25.</ref>\n\nIn 1417 he was made [[Admiral of the Fleet]] under [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]], and in 1418 was with King Henry V at the [[Siege of Rouen]]. In November 1418 he was designated [[Lord Steward|Steward of the King's Household]],<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Rymer, ''F\u0153dera'', vol. iv. pt. iii. p. 76.</ref> and was granted the barony of Hommet in Normandy (today [[Le Hommet-d'Arthenay|Le Hommet]]). He took part in the peace negotiations of 1419 and on 3 May 1421 was installed as a [[Knight of the Garter]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Beltz, ''Hist. of Garter'', p. clviii.</ref>\n\nHungerford was an executor of the will of King Henry V, and in 1422 became a member of the council of the [[Humphrey, Duke of Gloucester]], the [[Lord Protector]]. In 1424 he was made [[Steward of the Household]] of the infant King Henry VI, and on 7 January 1425/6 was summoned by [[writ]] to Parliament as [[Baron Hungerford]]. The summons was continued to him until his death. Hungerford became [[Treasurer of England]] in succession to Bishop Stafford, when Bishop Beaufort's resignation of the [[Great Seal of the Realm|Great Seal]] in March 1426-7 placed Gloucester in supreme power. He acted as Carver at Henry VI's coronation in Paris in December 1430,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: Waurin, ''Chron''., Rolls Ser.,iv. 11</ref> but on the change of ministry which followed Henry VI's return from France in February 1431-2, he ceased to be Treasurer. He attended the [[Congress of Arras|conference at Arras]] in 1435.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=258}} cites: ''Wars of Henry VI in France'', Rolls Ser., ed. Stevenson, ii. 431.</ref>\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\n[[File:Arms Peverell OfSampfordPeverell Devon.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of Peverell of [[Sampford Peverell]], Devon: ''Azure, three garbs argent a chief or''<ref>Pole, p.496</ref>]]\n[[File:HungerfordKnot.png|thumb|200px|The marriage of Sir Walter Hungerford to Catherine Peverell is symbolised in a heraldic badge showing the [[Hungerford knot]] uniting the Hungerford [[sickle]] and the Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garb]], the latter a badge of the ancient Peverel family, [[Honour of Peverel|feudal barons of Peverel]] (or of \"the Peak\") in [[Derbyshire]]]]\nHungerford married twice:\n* Firstly to Catherine (or Eleanor) Peverell, daughter of Sir Thomas Peverell, MP, of Parke and Hamatethy, Cornwall{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}} (a cadet branch of Peverell of [[Sampford Peverell]] in Devon<ref>Pole, p.227 re descent of manor of Wolmerston</ref>) by his wife Margaret Courtenay (1355\u20131422{{citation needed|date=September 2013|reason=for the dates}}) one of the two daughters and eventual sole heiresses of Sir [[Thomas Courtenay (of Wootton Courtenay)|Thomas Courtenay]] (died 1356)<ref>Date of birth \"1315 or before\" ({{harvnb|Knight|2016}} cites {{harvnb|Richardson|''Magna Carta Ancestry''}}; death date  \"1356\" ({{harvnb|Knight|2016}} cites {{harv|Richardson|''Magna Carta Ancestry''}}; and & {{harvnb|Vivian|1895|p=244}}</ref> of [[Wootton Courtenay]] in Somerset and of Woodhuish, Devon,{{sfn|Roskell|Kightly|1993}} by whom he had three sons and at least one daughter:\n** Walter Hungerford, eldest son and [[heir apparent]], who was made a [[prisoner of war]] in France in 1425, was ransomed by his father for three thousand marks, was in the [[retinue]] of [[John of Lancaster, 1st Duke of Bedford]] in France in 1435, and predeceased his father without issue.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n** [[Robert Hungerford, 2nd Baron Hungerford]], eldest surviving son and heir.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n** Edmund Hungerford, who was knighted by Henry VI after the [[Battle of Verneuil]] on Whit-Sunday 1426,<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites: Metcalfe, ''Book of Knights'', p.1</ref> and married Margaret Burnell, daughter and co-heiress of Edward Burnell, by whom he had two sons:\n*** Thomas Hungerford, ancestor of the Hungerfords of [[Down Ampney]] in Gloucestershire, of the Hungerfords of [[Windrush, Oxfordshire]] and of the Hungerfords of [[Black Bourton]], Oxfordshire.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n*** Edward Hungerford, ancestor of the Hungerfords of [[Foxham, Wiltshire|Cadenham]], Wiltshire.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}[[File:BishopBishopPeterCourtenay ChimneypieceExeterPalace SeeImpalingCourtenay.JPG|thumb|200px|Arms of Bishop [[Peter Courtenay]] (d.1492), showing the arms of the [[See of Exeter]] impaling Courtenay of Powderham, incorporating [[Badge (heraldry)|heraldic badges]] of [[dolphin]]s of Courtenay of Powderham and in the [[spandrel]]s, Hungerford [[sickle]]s and Peverell [[Sheaf (agriculture)|garbs]]. Detail from the Courtenay Mantelpiece, Bishop's Palace, Exeter]]\n** Elizabeth Hungerford (died 14 December 1476), who married Sir [[Philip Courtenay (died 1463)|Philip Courtenay]] (1404\u20131463) of [[Manor of Powderham|Powderham]], Devon.{{sfn|Vivian|1895|p=246}} On her marriage she took to her husband as her [[marriage portion]] the [[manor of Molland]] in North Devon, which she gave to her second son Sir Philip Courtenay of Molland (died 1488), who founded a junior branch of the Courtenay family there.{{sfn|Vivian|1895|p=246, 251-225}} A fragment of an ancient [[chest tomb]] in Molland Church displays heraldic motifs of two interlaced Hungerford sickles and a dolphin of Courtenay of Powderham. Her third son was [[Peter Courtenay]] (c.1432\u20131492) [[Bishop of Exeter]] and [[Bishop of Winchester]], whose splendid surviving mantlepiece in the [[Bishop's Palace, Exeter]] displays much heraldry including Hungerford sickles and Peverell garbs.<ref>A Delineation of the Courtenay Mantelpiece in the Episcopal Palace at Exeter by Roscoe Gibbs with a Biographical Notice of The Right Reverend Peter Courtenay, DD,... To which is added A Description of the Courtenay Mantelpiece compiled by Maria Halliday, privately published at the Office of the Torquay Directory, 1884, p.10</ref>\n* Secondly he married Eleanor Berkeley (died 1 August 1455), daughter of [[John Berkeley (1352\u20131428)|Sir John Berkeley]] of [[Beverstone Castle]], Gloucestershire,{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}} (by his second wife, Elizabeth Betteshorne).<ref name=\"parliament\">{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/berkeley-sir-john-i-1352-1428|title=BERKELEY, Sir John I (1352-1428), of Beverstone castle, Glos. - History of Parliament Online|website=www.historyofparliamentonline.org}}</ref> Eleanor Berkeley was a widow successively of [[John FitzAlan, 13th Earl of Arundel]] (died 1421) and of Sir Richard Poynings (died 1429){{sfn|Richardson II|2011|p=428}}{{sfn|Richardson III|2011|pp=394\u20135}}).<ref name=\"parliament\"></ref> Walter Hungerford and Eleanor de Berkeley were without progeny.{{sfn|Lee|1891|p=259}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nHungerford died on 9 August 1449 and was buried beside his first wife in [[Salisbury Cathedral]], where two beautiful mortuary chapels erected by the Hungerford family stood until removed and destroyed by the restorations of [[James Wyatt]] in 1790. [[William Henry Hamilton Rogers|William Hamilton Rogers]] (1877) wrote as follows concerning the monument:{{sfn|Rogers|1877|p=184}}{{sfn|Lee|1891|pp=258\u2013259}}\n:\"He was buried with his wife in the Hungerford Chapel in the nave, a beautiful structure composed chiefly of iron and which has since been removed to the choir. Their tombs, joined together and despoiled of their brass effigies, remain in the nave. The matrices exhibit the proportions of a knight on the one and of a lady on the other, both stones were powdered over with sickles and a [[ledger line]] outside all. The whole has now disappeared, except the stones in which the brasses were set. Forty shields of arms, according to Hutchins (who minutely describes these chapels previous to their removal) were set round outside exhibiting the various alliances of the family. Among these were Hungerford impaling Strange and Mohun, Peverell, Courtenay, St John, Mules, etc\".{{efn|The heraldry was also described at length by [[Richard Symonds (diarist)|Richard Symonds]] in his ''Diary of the Marches of the Royal Army'', (1644).{{sfn|Symonds|Roy|Long|1859|pp=137\u2013140}}}}\n\n==Benefactions==\nBy his marriages and royal grants Hungerford added largely to the family estates. He built chantries at [[Church of St Peter and St Paul, Heytesbury|Heytesbury]] and [[St Andrew's Church, Chippenham|Chippenham]], and made bequests to [[Salisbury Cathedral]] and to [[Bath Cathedral]]. In 1428 he presented valuable estates to the [[St Stephen's Chapel|Royal Chapel]] in the [[Palace of Westminster]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites: Jackson, ''Anc. Statutes of Heytesbury Almshouses'', Devizes, 1863.</ref> He founded an [[almshouse]] in 1442<ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.wiltshire.gov.uk/community/getcom.php?id=115|title=Heytesbury|website=Wiltshire Community History|publisher=Wiltshire Council|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> at [[Heytesbury]] for twelve poor men and one woman, with a schoolmaster's residence; after being re-endowed by Margaret de Botreaux, widow of his son Robert, and then rebuilt in 1769 after a fire, the charity continues today as the Hospital of St John.<ref>{{cite web|website=British History Online|title=Victoria County History: Wiltshire: Vol 3 pp337-340 \u2013 Hospitals: St John and St Katherine, Heytesbury|editor-first1=R.B.|editor-last1=Pugh|editor-first2=Elizabeth|editor-last2=Crittall|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/wilts/vol3/pp337-340|publisher=University of London|accessdate=24 March 2017|date=1956}}</ref><ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1284088|desc=Hospital of St. John|access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn his will he left to his daughter-in-law, Margaret de Botreaux (wife of Sir Robert Hungerford, 2nd Baron), his \"best legend of the Lives of the Saints\" and to John, Viscount Beaumont he bequeathed a cup formerly used by [[John of Gaunt]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1891|p=259}} cites [[Nicholas Harris Nicolas]]'s ''Testamenta Vetusta'', pp.&nbsp;257\u20139</ref>\n\nIn 1407 Hungerford donated the [[advowson]] of the church at his manor of [[Rushall, Wiltshire|Rushall]] in Wiltshire to the [[Canons regular|canons]] of [[Longleat Priory]], who were struggling to support themselves financially.{{sfn|Pugh|Crittall|1956|p=302\u2013303}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web |last=Knight |first=Patrick |date=September 2016 |url=http://www.knight-france.com/geneal/names/3942.htm |title=Sir Thomas DE COURTENAY, Knt., Of Woodhuish & Dunterton & ... [3942] |publisher= Genealogy - KNIGHTs from Continental Europe to England/Ireland, to Philadelphia (PA), to France |ref=harv |accessdate=3 December 2016}}<!-- This is not a reliable source, but its source is so can be used with [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]-->\n*{{cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |editor-last=Everingham|editor-first=Kimball G.|title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |publisher=Genealogical Pub. Co.|year=2005|ref={{sfnRef|Richardson|Magna Carta Ancestry}}|edition=2nd}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pole |first=Sir William |authorlink=William Pole (antiquary) |title=Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon |editor-last=Pole |editor-first= Sir John-William de la |editor-link=Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet |location=London |year=1791 |page=496}}\n*{{Cite book  |editor1-last=Pugh |editor1-first=R.B. |editor2-last=Crittall |editor2-first=Elizabeth |year=1956 |chapter=Houses of Augustinian canons: Priory of Longleat |title=A History of the County of Wiltshire |volume=3 |pages=302\u2013303 |chapter-url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=36541 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Richardson |first=Douglas |year=2011 |title=Magna Carta Ancestry: A Study in Colonial and Medieval Families |edition=2nd  |editor-last=Everingham |editor-first=Kimball G.|volume=II |location=Salt Lake City |isbn=978-1449966386 |ref={{sfnref |Richardson II |2011}} }}\n*{{Cite book  |last=Richardson |first=Douglas  |year=