b''' [[Afghan afghani|Afghani]]\n|{{UN Population|Afghanistan}}\n|$21.657 billion\n|$601\n|3%\n|6%\n|-\n|{{Country|Bangladesh}}\n|'''\u09f3''' [[Bangladeshi taka|Bangladeshi Taka]]\n|{{UN Population|Bangladesh}}\n|$314.656 billion\n|$2,067\n|8.2%\n|5.44%\n|-\n|{{Country|Bhutan}}\n|'''Nu.''' [[Bhutanese ngultrum|Ngultrum]]\n|{{UN Population|Bhutan}}\n|$2.31 billion\n|$3,215\n|5.9%\n|4.1%\n|-\n|{{Country|India}}\n|'''\u20b9''' [[Indian rupee|Indian Rupee]]\n|{{UN Population|India}}\n|$2.971 trillion\n|$2,198\n|7.0%\n|4.8%\n|-\n|{{Country|Maldives}}\n|'''\u0783''' [[Maldivian rufiyaa|Rufiyaa]]\n|{{UN Population|Maldives}}\n|$4.825 billion\n|$14,501\n|4.1%\n|2.5%\n|-\n|{{Country|Nepal}}\n|'''\u0930\u0941''' [[Nepalese rupee|Rupee]]\n|{{UN Population|Nepal}}\n|$27 billion\n|$919\n|7.7%\n|6.2%\n|-\n|{{Country|Pakistan}}\n|'''\u20a8''' [[Pakistani rupee|Pakistani Rupee]]\n|{{UN Population|Pakistan}}\n|$278.019 billion\n|$1,357\n|5.2%\n|4.3%\n|-\n|{{Country|Sri Lanka}}\n|'''\u0dbb\u0dd4/\u0bb0\u0bc2''' [[Sri Lankan rupee|Rupee]]\n|{{UN Population|Sri Lanka}}\n|$92.504 billion\n|$4,265\n|3.0%\n|5.8%\n|}\n\n==Health and nutrition==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|\n!Afghanistan|| Bangladesh|| Bhutan || India || Maldives || Nepal || Pakistan || Sri Lanka\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Population undernourished (2015)<ref name=\"fao.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4624e.pdf|title=UN|access-date=3 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924011158/http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4624e.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|26.8%|| 16.4% || N/A || 15.2%|| 5.2% || 7.8% || 22% || 22%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Population below poverty line (CIA Factbook)<ref name=\"CIA Factbook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2046.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=23 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109070125/https://www.cia.gov/Library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2046.html|archive-date=9 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|35.8%|| 7.5% || 12% || 21.2%|| 16% || 25.2% || 24.3% || 8.9%\n|}\n\nAccording to WHO, South Asia is home to two out of the three countries in the world still affected by polio, Pakistan and Afghanistan, with 306 & 28 polio cases registered in 2014 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polioeradication.org/Infectedcountries/Afghanistan.aspx|title=GPEI|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706045955/http://www.polioeradication.org/Infectedcountries/Afghanistan.aspx|archivedate=6 July 2015}}</ref> Attempts to eradicate polio have been badly hit by opposition from militants in both countries, who say the program is cover to spy on their operations. Their attacks on immunization teams have claimed 78 lives since December 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1151027 |title=Lost \u2014 The battle against polio |last1=Haider |first1=Sajjad |last2=Khan |first2=Shameen |newspaper=Dawn |date=31 December 2014 |access-date=4 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605081706/http://www.dawn.com/news/1151027 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:PRT Farah visits Children&#039;s Supplemental Feeding Center in Farah City 130119-N-LR347-327.jpg|thumb|A weekly child examination performed at a hospital in [[Farah, Afghanistan]]]]\nAccording to the World Bank's 2011 report, based on 2005 ICP PPP, about 24.6% of the South Asian population falls below the international poverty line of $1.25/day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://povertydata.worldbank.org/poverty/region/SAS|title=Poverty & Equity Data Portal|website=povertydata.worldbank.org|access-date=6 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215193607/http://povertydata.worldbank.org/poverty/region/SAS|archive-date=15 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Afghanistan and Bangladesh rank the highest, with 30.6% and 43.3% of their respective populations below the poverty line. Bhutan, Maldives and Sri Lanka have the lowest number of people below the poverty line, with 2.4%, 1.5% and 4.1% respectively. India has lifted the most people in the region above the poverty line between 2008 and 2011, around 140 million. As of 2011, 21.9% of India's population lives below the poverty line, compared to 41.6% in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/xrATLLP8ojKEVEQgJV0UxJ/The-World-Bank-on-Indias-poverty.html|title=The World Bank on India\u2019s poverty|first=Manas|last=Chakravarty|newspaper=Live Mint|date=13 October 2014|access-date=6 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623075308/http://www.livemint.com/Opinion/xrATLLP8ojKEVEQgJV0UxJ/The-World-Bank-on-Indias-poverty.html|archive-date=23 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/country/india|title=India \u2013 Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=6 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619201931/http://data.worldbank.org/country/india|archive-date=19 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[World Bank]] estimates that [[India]] is one of the highest-ranking countries in the world for the number of children suffering from [[malnutrition]]. The prevalence of underweight children in India is among the highest in the world and is nearly double that of [[Sub Saharan Africa]] with dire consequences for mobility, mortality, productivity, and economic growth.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/0,,contentMDK:20916955~pagePK:146736~piPK:146830~theSitePK:223547,00.html|title= World Bank Report|accessdate= 2009-03-13|publisher= The World Bank|year= 2009|quote= World Bank Report on Malnutrition in India|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081218015506/http://www.worldbank.org.in/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/INDIAEXTN/0,,contentMDK:20195738~menuPK:295591~pagePK:141137~piPK:141127~theSitePK:295584,00.html|archive-date= 18 December 2008|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the World Bank, 70% of the South Asian population and about 75% of South Asia's poor live in rural areas, and most rely on agriculture for their livelihood<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20750711~menuPK:452772~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html|title=Agriculture in South Asia|publisher=World Bank|access-date=21 February 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706154611/http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20750711~menuPK:452772~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html|archive-date=6 July 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> according to the UN's Food and Agricultural Organisation. In 2015, approximately 281 million people in the region were malnourished. The report says that Nepal reached both the WFS target as well as MDG and is moving towards bringing down the number of hungry people to less than 5% of the population.<ref name=\"fao.org\"/> Bangladesh reached the MDG target with the National Food Policy framework{{snd}}with only 16.5% of the population undernourished. In India, the malnourished comprise just over 15 percent of the population. While the number of malnourished people in the neighborhood has shown a decline over the last 25 years, the number of under-nourished in Pakistan displays an upward trend. There were 28.7 million hungry in Pakistan in the 1990s{{snd}}a number that has steadily increased to 41.3 million in 2015, with 22% of the population malnourished. Approximately 194.6 million people are undernourished in India, which accounts for the highest number of people suffering from hunger in any single country.<ref name=\"fao.org\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1184959|title=India home to world's largest number of hungry people: report|newspaper=Dawn|date=29 May 2015|access-date=4 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150604142045/http://www.dawn.com/news/1184959|archive-date=4 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe 2006 report stated, \"the low status of women in South Asian countries and their lack of nutritional knowledge are important determinants of the high prevalence of underweight children in the region.\" Corruption and the lack of initiative on the part of the government have been one of the major problems associated with nutrition in India. Illiteracy in villages is one of the major issues that need more government attention. The report mentioned that although there has been a reduction in malnutrition due to the [[Green Revolution]] in South Asia, there is concern that South Asia has \"inadequate feeding and caring practices for young children\".<ref name=\"southasiahunger\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6046718.stm|title='Hunger critical' in South Asia|publisher=BBC News|date=2006-10-13|accessdate=2010-01-04|first=Geeta|last=Pandey|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112084920/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6046718.stm|archive-date=12 January 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== General statistical data ==\nBelow is the latest general statistical data for South Asian nations. Their total population, area and GDPs have been cited along with their shares of percentage of this attribute of total South Asia in bracket. [[Republic of India]] accounts for most of landmass, population and GDP and hence, heavily influences average of South Asian development attributes. [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Maldives]] are leaders in the region in terms of [[Human Development Index]] and GDP per capita while [[Afghanistan]] scores lowest in terms of both the attributes in the region.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ececec;\"\n![[Country]]<br /><ref name=\"CIA Names\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2142.html |title=Field Listing :: Names |publisher=CIA |accessdate=28 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701201536/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2142.html |archive-date=1 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"CIA Names\"/><ref name=\"UN_Names\">{{cite web |url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/UNGEGN/docs/9th-uncsgn-docs/UNGEGN%20WG%20Country%20Names%20Document%20-%20August%202009.pdf |title=UNGEGN List of Country Names |publisher=United Nations Group of Experts on Geographical Names |year=2007 |accessdate=28 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728144159/http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/UNGEGN/docs/9th-uncsgn-docs/UNGEGN%20WG%20Country%20Names%20Document%20-%20August%202009.pdf |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Europa\">{{cite web |url=http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-5000500.htm#fn-tw1 |title=List of countries, territories and currencies |publisher=Europa |date=9 August 2011 |accessdate=10 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807122658/http://publications.europa.eu/code/en/en-5000500.htm#fn-tw1 |archive-date=7 August 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n! Capital<br /><ref name=\"Europa\"/><ref name=\"Capital\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2057.html |title=Field Listing :: Capital |publisher=CIA |accessdate=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629164805/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2057.html |archive-date=29 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/geonames/ |title=UNGEGN World Geographical Names |publisher=United Nations Group of Experts on Geographical Names |date=29 July 2011 |accessdate=3 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110801231428/http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/geonames/ |archive-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n![[List of countries by area|Area]]<br />(km<sup>2</sup>) (%Share)<br /><ref name=\"Area\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2147.html |title=Field Listing :: Area |publisher=CIA |accessdate=7 August 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69UpcaHtw?url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2147.html |archive-date=28 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n![[List of countries by population|Population]] in thousands<br />(2019) (%Share)<ref name = \"UN WPP 2019\">{{Cite web|title = World Population prospects \u2013 Population division|url = https://population.un.org/wpp/|accessdate = 16 July 2019|publisher = [[United Nations]]|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190205234912/https://population.un.org/wpp/|archive-date = 5 February 2019|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name = \"UN WPP 2019 2\">{{Cite web|title = Overall total population|url = https://population.un.org/wpp/Download/Files/1_Indicators%20(Standard)/EXCEL_FILES/1_Population/WPP2019_POP_F01_1_TOTAL_POPULATION_BOTH_SEXES.xlsx|format = xlsx|accessdate = 16 July 2019|publisher = [[United Nations]]}}</ref>\n![[List of countries by population density|Density]]<br />(per km<sup>2</sup>)\n![[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|Nominal GDP]]<br /> (in millions) (2019) (%Share)<ref name = \"IMF Oct 2019\">{{Cite web|title=World Economic Outlook - GDP current prices, in billions of dollars|url=https://www.imf.org/external/datamapper/NGDPD@WEO/OEMDC/ADVEC/WEOWORLD|work=International Monetary Fund|date=October 2019|accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n![[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|GDP]] [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|per]] [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|capita]]\n(2019)<ref name = \"IMF Oct 2019 - 2\">{{Cite web|title=World Economic Outlook - GDP current prices, per capita|url=https://www.imf.org/external/datamapper/NGDPDPC@WEO/OEMDC/ADVEC/WEOWORLD/|work=International Monetary Fund|date=October 2019|accessdate=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n![[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|GDP (PPP)]]<br /> (in millions) (2019) (%Share)\n![[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP (PPP) per capita]] (2019)\n![[Human Development Index|HDI]]\n(2018)<ref name=\"UNDP2019\"/>\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Afghanistan}}'''\n|[[Kabul]]\n|652,230 (12.7%)\n|38,042 (2.07%)\n|58.3\n|align=right|$18,734 (0.51%)\n|$513\n|align=right|$76,714 (0.55%)\n|$2,101\n|{{Decrease}}0.496 (''<span style=\"color:red\">low</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Bangladesh}}'''\n|[[Dhaka]]\n|147,570 (2.87%)\n|163,046 (8.88%)\n|1,104.9\n|align=right|$317,465 (8.67%)\n|$1,906\n|align=right|$829,270 (5.92%)\n|$4,992\n|{{Increase}}0.614 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Bhutan}}'''\n|[[Thimphu]]\n|38,394 (0.75%)\n|763 (0.04%)\n|19.8\n|align=right|$2,842 (0.08%)\n|$3,423\n|align=right|$9,310 (0.066%)\n|$10,193\n|{{Increase}}0.617 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|India}}'''\n|[[New Delhi]]\n|3,287,263 (64.02%)\n|1,366,418 (74.45%)\n|415.6\n|align=right|$2,935,570 (80.16%)\n|$2,172\n|align=right|$11436,697 (81.68%)\n|$8,484\n|{{Increase}}0.647 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Maldives}}'''\n|[[Mal\u00e9]]\n|298 (0.006%)\n|531 (0.03%)\n|1,781.8\n|align=right|$5,786 (0.16%)\n|$15,563\n|align=right|$6,708 (0.048%)\n|$21,320\n|{{Increase}}0.719 (''<span style=\"color:lightgreen\">high</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Nepal}}'''\n|[[Kathmandu]]\n|147,181 (2.87%)\n|28,609 (1.56%)\n|194.3\n|align=right|$29,813 (0.81%)\n|$1,048\n|align=right|$87,472 (0.62%)\n|$2,984\n|{{Increase}}0.579 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Pakistan}}'''\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|796,095 (15.5%)\n|216,565 (11.8%)\n|245.8\n|align=right|$284,214 (7.76%)\n|$1,388\n|align=right|$1,235,663 (8.82%)\n|$5,839\n|{{Decrease}}0.560 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|-\n|'''{{Country|Sri Lanka}}'''\n|[[Colombo]]\n|65,610 (1.28%)\n|21,324 (1.62%)\n|325\n|align=right|$86,566 (2.36%)\n|$3,947\n|align=right|$319,791 (2.28%)\n|$14,680\n|{{Increase}}0.780 (''<span style=\"color:lightgreen\">high</span>'')\n|-\n!colspan=2|'''South Asia'''||'''5,134,641 (100%)'''||'''1,835,297 (100%)'''||'''357.4'''||'''$3,662,255 (100%)'''||'''$2,064'''||'''$14,001, 625 (100%)'''||'''$7,629'''||{{Increase}}0.642 (''<span style=\"color:orange\">medium</span>'')\n|}\n\n== Governance and politics==\n=== Systems of government ===\n{{See also|List of legislatures in South Asia|List of countries by system of government}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ececec;\"\n! Country\n! Capital\n! Forms of government\n! Head of state\n! Head of government\n! Legislature\n! Official language\n! width=90px | Coat of arms / National Emblems\n|-\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"| {{Country|Afghanistan}}\n| [[Kabul]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Presidential system|presidential]] [[Islamic republic]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |<center>[[President of Afghanistan|President]]</center>\n| [[House of Elders (Afghanistan)|House of Elders]],<br />[[House of the People (Afghanistan)|House of the People]]\n| [[Pashto]], [[Dari language|Dari]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Emblem of Afghanistan.svg|50px|Emblem of Afghanistan]]\n|-\n|style=\"white-space:nowrap;\"| {{Country|Bangladesh}}\n| [[Dhaka]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Republic|constitutional republic]]\n| [[President of Bangladesh|President]]\n| [[Prime Minister of Bangladesh|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Jatiya Sangsad]]\n| [[Bengali language|Bengali]], English\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Coat of arms of Bangladesh.svg|50px|Coat of arms of Bangladesh]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Bhutan}}\n| [[Thimphu]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[constitutional monarchy]]\n| [[Druk Gyalpo|King]]\n| [[List of Prime Ministers of Bhutan|Prime Minister]]\n| [[National Council (Bhutan)|National Council]],<br />[[National Assembly (Bhutan)|National Assembly]]\n| [[Dzongkha language|Dzongkha]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Bhutan emblem.svg|50px|Emblem of Bhutan]]\n|-\n| {{Country|India}}\n| [[New Delhi]]\n| [[Federal republic|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] constitutional republic\n| [[President of India|President]]\n| [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Rajya Sabha]],<br />[[Lok Sabha]]\n| [[Hindi]], English\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Emblem of India.svg|50px|Emblem of India]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Maldives}}\n| [[Mal\u00e9]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Presidential system|presidential]] constitutional republic\n| colspan=\"2\" |<center>[[President of the Maldives|President]]</center>\n| [[People's Majlis]]\n| [[Maldivian language|Maldivian]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Emblem of Maldives.svg|50px|Emblem of Maldives]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Nepal}}\n| [[Kathmandu]]\n| [[Federal republic|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] constitutional republic\n| [[President of Nepal|President]]\n| [[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister]]\n| [[National Assembly (Nepal)|National Assembly]],<br />[[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]]\n| [[Nepali language|Nepali]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Emblem of Nepal.svg|50px|Coat of arms of Nepal]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Pakistan}}\n| [[Islamabad]]\n| [[Federal republic|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Islamic republic]]\n| [[President of Pakistan|President]]\n| [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Senate of Pakistan|Senate]],<br />[[National Assembly of Pakistan|National Assembly]]\n| [[Urdu]], English\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Coat of arms of Pakistan.svg|50px|Coat of arms of Pakistan]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Sri Lanka}}\n| [[Colombo]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Semi-presidential system|semi-presidential]] constitutional republic\n| [[President of Sri Lanka|President]]\n| [[Prime Minister of Sri Lanka|Prime Minister]]\n| [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Parliament]]\n| [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], English\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Coat of arms of Sri Lanka.svg|50px|Coat of arms of Sri Lanka]]\n|}\n\n;Countries and territories from extended definitions\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ececec;\"\n! Country or region\n! Capital\n! Administrative division type\n! Head of government\n! Area (km<sup>2</sup>)\n! Population\n! Official language\n! width=90px | Coat of arms\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|British Indian Ocean Territory}} [[British Indian Ocean Territory]]\n| [[Diego Garcia]]\n| [[British Overseas Territory]]\n| [[Commissioner for the British Indian Ocean Territory|Commissioner]]\n|54,400\n|2,500\n| English\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Coat of arms of the British Indian Ocean Territory (Shield).svg|50px]]\n|-\n| {{Country|Myanmar}}\n| [[Naypyidaw]]\n| [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Republic|constitutional republic]]\n| [[State Counsellor of Myanmar|State Counsellor]]\n|676,578\n|51,486,253\n| [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:State seal of Myanmar.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|China}} [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]\n| [[Lhasa]]\n| [[Autonomous Region of China]]\n|[[List of modern political leaders of Tibet#TAR Government Chairmen|Chairman]]\n|1,228,400\n|3,180,000\n| [[Standard Tibetan|Tibetan]], [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:National Emblem of the People's Republic of China.svg|50px]]\n|}\n\n[[India]] is a [[Secular state|secular]] [[Federation|federative]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary republic]] with [[Prime Minister of India|premier]] as head of government. With most populous functional democracy in world<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/learningzone/clips/india-worlds-largest-democracy/10104.html |title=India: world's largest democracy |website=BBC Learning Zone Class Clips |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114055717/http://www.bbc.co.uk/learningzone/clips/india-worlds-largest-democracy/10104.html |archive-date=2011-01-14}}</ref> and world's longest written constitution,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/kids/Celebrate-the-supreme-law/article14011992.ece|title=Celebrate the supreme law|last=Krithika|first=R.|date=21 January 2016|work=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=24 July 2018|publisher=[[N. Ram]]|issn=0971-751X|oclc=13119119}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=India's Constitution|last=Pylee|first=Moolamattom Varkey|publisher=R. Chand & Company|year=1994|isbn=978-8121904032|edition=5th rev. and enl.|location=[[New Delhi]]|pages=3|oclc=35022507}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.history.com/news/which-country-has-the-worlds-shortest-written-constitution|title=Which country has the world's shortest written constitution?|last=Nix|first=Elizabeth|date=9 August 2016|work=[[History (U.S. TV network)|History]]|access-date=24 July 2018|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]}}</ref> India has been stably sustaining the political system it adopted in 1950 with no regime change except that by a democratic election. India's sustained democratic freedoms are unique among the world's newer establishments. Since the [[Republic Day (India)|formation of its republic]] abolishing [[Government of India Act 1935|British law]], it has remained a democracy with civil liberties, an active Supreme Court, and a largely independent press.{{sfn|Metcalf|Metcalf|2006|p = 304}} India leads region in [[Democracy Index|democracy index]]. It has a [[multi-party system]] in its internal regional politics{{sfn|Burnell|Calvert|1999|p = 125}} whereas alternative transfer of powers to alliances of Indian [[United Progressive Alliance|left-wing]] and [[National Democratic Alliance|right-wing]] political parties in national government provide it with characteristics of a [[Two-party system|two-party state]].<ref name=\"Political Parties in India\">{{cite web|title = Political Parties in India|url = http://electionaffairs.com/parties/parties.html|publisher = electionaffairs.com|accessdate = 7 August 2012|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150707215933/http://electionaffairs.com/parties/parties.html|archivedate = 7 July 2015}}</ref> India has been facing notable internal religious conflicts and separatism however [[List of countries by Fragile States Index|consistently becoming more and more stable with time]].\n\nFoundation of Pakistan lies in [[Pakistan movement]] started in [[British Raj|colonial India]] based on [[Muslim nationalism in South Asia|Islamic nationalism]]. Pakistan is a [[Federal republic|federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Islamic Republic]] and was the world's first country to adopt [[Islamic Republic]] system to modify its republican status under its otherwise secular constitution in 1956. Pakistan's governance is one of the most conflicted in the world. The [[Military coups in Pakistan|military rule and the unstable government in Pakistan]] has become a concern for the South Asian region. Out of 22 appointed [[List of Prime Ministers of Pakistan|Pakistani Prime ministers]], none has been able to complete a full term in office.<ref>{{Cite web|title = No One Has Ever Completed a Term as Pakistan\u2019s PM|url = https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/07/25/no-one-has-ever-completed-a-term-as-pakistans-pm/|date = July 25, 2018|accessdate = October 18, 2019|publisher = [[Foreign Policy]]|website = foreignpolicy.com}}</ref> The nature of [[Politics of Pakistan|Pakistani politics]] can be characterized as a [[multi-party system]].\n\n[[Bangladesh]] is a [[Unitary state|unitary]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary republic]]. Law of Bangladesh defines it as both Islamic<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdlaws.minlaw.gov.bd/sections_detail.php?id=367&sections_id=24549%7CSection|title=2A. The state religion|publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref> as well as secular.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdlaws.minlaw.gov.bd/sections_detail.php?id=367&sections_id=24560%7CSection|title=12.}}</ref> The nature of [[Politics of Bangladesh|Bangladeshi politics]] can be characterized as a [[multi-party system]].\n\n[[Afghanistan]] has been a [[Unitary state|unitary]] [[Presidential system|presidential]] [[Islamic Republic]] since 2004. Afghanistan has been suffering from one of the most unstable regimes on earth as a result of [[War in Afghanistan|multiple foreign invasions, civil wars, revolutions, and terrorist groups]]. Persisting instability for decades have left the country's economy stagnated and torn, and Afghanistan remains one of most poor and [[Least developed country|least developed countries]] on the planet.<ref name=\"AfgCIA\"/>\n\nThe [[Unitary state|unitary]] [[semi-presidential system|semi-presidential]] constitutional republic of [[Sri Lanka]] is oldest sustained democracy in Asia. Tensions between [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] and [[Tamil people|Tamils]] led to [[Sri Lankan civil war]] that undermined country's stability for more than two and a half-decade.<ref name=\"mod-defeat\">{{cite news |title=LTTE defeated; Sri Lanka liberated from terror |date=18 May 2009 |url=http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_10 |work=Ministry of Defence |accessdate=19 October 2019|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521113622/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20090518_10 |archivedate=21 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Sri Lanka however, has been leading region in [[Human Development Index|HDI]] with per capita GDP well ahead of India and Bangladesh. [[Nepal]] was last Hindu state in the world before [[Republic Day (Nepal)|becoming a secular democratic republic]] in 2008. The country has been ranked among the world's poorest in terms of GDP per capita but has made considerable progress in development indicators outpacing many other South Asian states. [[Bhutan]] is a Buddhist state with a [[constitutional monarchy]]. The country was ranked as least corrupt and peaceful with most economic freedom in the region in 2016. [[Myanmar]]'s politics is dominated by a military [[Military junta|Junta]], which has sidelined the democratic forces led by [[Aung San Suu Kyi]]. [[Maldives]] is a unitary presidential republic with [[Sunni Islam]] strictly as the state religion.\n\n[[Populism]] is a general characteristic of internal politics of South Asian nations.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Global Populist Surge Is More than Just a Western Story\u2014Just Look at Asia|url = https://thediplomat.com/2016/12/the-global-populist-surge-is-more-than-just-a-western-story-just-look-at-asia/|date = December 10, 2016|accessdate = October 23, 2019|publisher = [[The Diplomat]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Regional politics ===\n{{Update section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Main|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|SAARC}}\n\n;Multiateral organizations\n[[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] or SAARC has been the primary regional supranational body comprising all current South Asian nations. The idea of cooperation among South Asian countries was first discussed in New Delhi in April 1947.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jang.com.pk/important_events/saarc_2004/history.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064044/http://jang.com.pk/important_events/saarc_2004/history.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |title=12th SAARC Summit Islamabad: History and Evolution of SAARC |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1970s, South Asian countries agreed upon forming a trade bloc within the region. [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] in 1979 accelerated efforts to form a union to restrengthen deteriorating regional security.<ref name=\"NIHCR in Islamabad\">\n{{cite web|last=Muhammad|first=Jamshed Iqbal|title=SAARC: Origin, Growth, Potential and Achievements |url=http://www.nihcr.edu.pk/Latest_English_Journal/SAARC_Jamshed_Iqbal.pdf|work=National Institute of Historical and Cultural Research in Islamabad|accessdate=11 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111092347/http://www.nihcr.edu.pk/Latest_English_Journal/SAARC_Jamshed_Iqbal.pdf |archive-date=11 November 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref> After agreements, the union was finally established in Dhaka in December 1985.<ref name=\"About SAARC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mohe.gov.af/saarc.afg/about%20us.html |title=About SAARC |website=SAARC Secretariat |accessdate=11 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111090614/http://www.mohe.gov.af/saarc.afg/about%20us.html |archivedate=11 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, deterioration of [[India-Pakistan relations|India-Pakistan ties]] have led India to emphasize more on sub-regional groups [[South Asia Subregional Economic Cooperation|SASEC]] and [[BBIN]]. Due to [[2016 Uri terror attack]] on Indian security forces, India, Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Sri Lanka and Maldives pulled out of [[19th SAARC summit|19th summit of SAARC]] that was supposed to be held in Pakistan which led to its ultimate cancellation.<ref name=\"rediff.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/report/india-pulls-out-of-saarc-summit-in-pakistan/20160927.htm|title=Pak isolated after India, 3 other countries pull out of SAARC summit - Rediff.com India News|publisher=|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/saarc-summit-maldives-joins-india-pakistan-isolation-complete/1/777596.html|title=SAARC: Maldives joins India, 4 others in boycott; Paks isolation complete|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> South Asia continues to remain least integrated region in the world. Meanwhile, in [[East Asia]], regional trade accounts for 50% of total trade, it accounts for only a little more than 5% in South Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Realizing the Promise of Regional Trade in South Asia|url = https://www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2018/10/09/realizing-the-promise-of-regional-trade-in-south-asia|date = October 9, 2018|accessdate = October 23, 2019|publisher = [[World Bank]]}}</ref>\n\n;By country\n[[India]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/parliament/expert/displayFtu.do?language=en&id=74&ftuId=FTU_6.4.11.html |title=The EU's External Relations |publisher=Europarl.europa.eu |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Vikram Aditya |url=http://www.theindianrepublic.com/tbp/foreign-policy-seizing-initiative-maintaining-momentum-100037338.html |title=Foreign Policy: Seizing The Initiative And Maintaining The Momentum |date=26 May 2014 |website=The Indian Republic |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606205819/http://www.theindianrepublic.com/tbp/foreign-policy-seizing-initiative-maintaining-momentum-100037338.html |archive-date=2014-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Gautam Mukherjee |url=http://m.niticentral.com/2014/05/23/why-invitation-to-saarc-countries-is-modis-master-stroke-226470.html |title=Why invitation to SAARC countries is Modi\u2019s masterstroke |date=27 May 2014 |website=Niti Central |accessdate=2014-06-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607005213/http://m.niticentral.com/2014/05/23/why-invitation-to-saarc-countries-is-modis-master-stroke-226470.html |archivedate=7 June 2014  }}</ref> [[Pakistan]],<ref name=\"Buzan2004\">{{cite book|author=Barry Buzan|title=The United States and the great powers: world politics in the twenty-first century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XvtS5hKg9jYC&pg=PR8|accessdate=27 December 2011|year=2004|publisher=Polity|isbn=978-0-7456-3374-9|pages=71, 99|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521150546/http://books.google.com/books?id=XvtS5hKg9jYC&pg=PR8|archive-date=21 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Solomon>{{cite web|author=Hussein Solomon |title=South African Foreign Policy and Middle Power Leadership |url=http://www.iss.co.za/Pubs/Monographs/No13/Solomon.html |accessdate=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020624231948/http://www.iss.co.za/Pubs/Monographs/No13/Solomon.html |archivedate=24 June 2002 }}</ref> and [[Bangladesh]] are the dominant political powers in the region. India is by far the largest country in the area covering around three-fourths the land area of the South Asian region.{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} India has the largest population of around three times the combined population of the 6 other countries in the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0004379.html |title=Area and Population of Countries (mid-2006 estimates) |publisher=Infoplease |accessdate=2010-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117021656/http://www.infoplease.com/ipa/A0004379.html |archive-date=17 January 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> India is also the world's largest [[democracy]] . India's defense budget is $66.5 billion which exceeds to the whole Pakistan's Federal budget of $42 billion for 2018-19 greatly.<ref name=\"TN\">{{cite news|title=Here is all you want to know about Budget 2018-19|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/310231-here-is-all-you-want-to-know-about-budget-2018-19|accessdate=9 September 2018|work=[[The News International]]|date=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh is a [[unitary state]] and [[parliamentary democracy]].<ref>\n{{cite web|title=The world factbook-Bangladesh|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html |publisher=CIA|access-date=6 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720222528/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html|archive-date=20 July 2015|url-status=live}}\n</ref> Bangladesh also stands out as one of the few Muslim-majority democracies. \"It is a moderate and generally secular and tolerant \u2014 though sometimes this is getting stretched at the moment \u2014 alternative to [[violent extremism]] in a very troubled part of the world\", said [[Dan Mozena]], the U.S. ambassador to [[Bangladesh]]. Although Bangladesh's legal code is [[secular]], more citizens are embracing a conservative version of [[Islam]], with some pushing for [[sharia law]], analysts say. Experts say that the rise in conservatism reflects the influence of foreign-financed Islamic charities and the more austere version of Islam brought home by migrant workers in [[Persian Gulf]] countries.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gowen|first1=Annie|title=Bangladesh's political unrest threatens economic gains, democracy|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bangladeshs-political-unrest-threatens-economic-gains-democracy/2014/03/22/baf1807c-a369-11e3-84d4-e59b1709222c_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=6 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702060029/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bangladeshs-political-unrest-threatens-economic-gains-democracy/2014/03/22/baf1807c-a369-11e3-84d4-e59b1709222c_story.html|archive-date=2 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDiplomacy among the countries of South Asia has been mainly driven by populist [[politics]], with the centre-stage taken by [[India]]-[[Pakistan]] conflict ever since their independence in 1947, and then the creation of Bangladesh under tense circumstances in 1971. During the height of [[Cold war]], the elite political leaders of Pakistan aligned with the [[United States|US]]. At the same time, India played crucial [[India and the Non-Aligned Movement|role]] informing the [[Non-Aligned Movement]] and while maintaining goodwill relations with the [[Union of Soviet Socialist Republics|USSR]].\n\nPakistan's governance is one of the most conflicted in the region. The military rule and the unstable government in Pakistan have become a concern for the South Asian region. In [[Nepal]], the government has struggled to come in the side of democracy, and it only showed signs in the recent past, basically in the 21st century, to support the democratic system. The political situation in [[Sri Lanka]] has been dominated by an increasingly assertive [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] nationalism, and the emergence of a [[Sri Lankan Tamil people|Tamil]] separatist movement under [[LTTE]], which was suppressed in May 2009. [[Myanmar]]'s politics is dominated by a military [[Military junta|Junta]], which has sidelined the democratic forces led by [[Aung San Suu Kyi]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Governance and education index rankings of South Asian countries\n! colspan=\"2\"|\n!Afghanistan|| Bangladesh|| Bhutan || India || Maldives || Nepal || Pakistan || Sri Lanka\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Inequality-adjusted HDI (2018)<ref name=\"UNDP2019\"/> (''global ranking of 150'')\n|No data|| 101 || 107 || 99 || 87 || 112 || 120 || 54\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Corruption Perception Index (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transparency.org/cpi2019?/news/feature/cpi-2019|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Transparency International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>  (''global ranking of 168'')\n|173|| 146 || 25 || 80 || 130 || 113 || 120 || 93\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | The Worldwide Governance<br />Indicators (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://info.worldbank.org/governance/wgi/#reports|title=Worldwide Governance Indicators|date=2015|website=World Bank|access-date=2017-08-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705084108/http://info.worldbank.org/governance/wgi/#reports|archive-date=5 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Government Effectiveness\n|8%|| 24% || 68% || 56% || 41% || 13% || 27% || 53%\n|-\n| Political stability and absence<br />of violence/terrorism\n|1%|| 11% || 89% || 17% || 61% || 16% || 1% || 47%\n|-\n| Rule of law\n|2%|| 27% || 70% || 56% || 35% || 27% || 24% || 60%\n|-\n| Voice and accountability\n|16%|| 31% || 46% || 61% || 30% || 33% || 27% || 36%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[List of countries by percentage of population living in poverty|Population below poverty line]] (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SI.POV.NAHC?locations=CO&view=map&year_high_desc=true|title=Poverty headcount ratio at national poverty lines (% of population) {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2017-08-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826234751/http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SI.POV.NAHC?locations=CO&view=map&year_high_desc=true|archive-date=26 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|35.8%|| 31.5% || 23.7% || 21.9%|| 16% || 25.2% || 21.4% || 8.9%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Primary School Enrollment<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.PRM.NENR|title=School enrollment, primary (% net) {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2017-08-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701185547/http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.PRM.NENR|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|29%||90%||85%||92%||94%||96%||73%||98%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |Secondary School Enrollment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.SEC.ENRR/countries|title=Gross enrolment ratio, secondary, both sexes (%) \u2013 Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=3 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516152545/http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SE.SEC.ENRR/countries|archive-date=16 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|49%||54%||78%||68%||N/A||72%||38%||96%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Asia}}\n<!-- {{Wikipedia-Books}} -->\n<!-- {{main|Outline of South Asia|Index of South Asia-related articles}} -->\n<!-- *[[Bibliography of South Asia]] -->\n* [[Genetics and archaeogenetics of South Asia]]\n* [[Indian subcontinent]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings and structures in South Asia]]\n* ''[[South Asia Disaster Report]]''\n* [[South Asian cuisine]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation|last1=Burnell|first1=P. J.|last2=Calvert|first2=P.|date=1 May 1999|title=The Resilience of Democracy: Persistent Practice, Durable Idea|edition=1st|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]]|isbn=978-0-7146-8026