{"title_page": "1992 United States presidential election in Vermont", "text_new": "{{main|1992 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1992 [[United States presidential election]] in Vermont\n| country = Vermont\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1988 United States presidential election in Vermont\n| previous_year = 1988\n| next_election = 1996 United States presidential election in Vermont\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Al Gore]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''3'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''133,592'''\n| percentage1 = '''46.11%'''\t\n| image2 = George H. W. Bush presidential portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee2 = [[George H. W. Bush]] \n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Dan Quayle]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 88,122\n| percentage2 = 30.42%\t\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 65,991\t   \n| percentage3 = 22.78%\n| map_image = Vermont Election Results by Shaded County 1992.svg\n| map_size = 200px\n| map_caption = County Results\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#d3e7ff|30\u201340%}}\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40\u201350%}}\n{{legend|#86b6f2|50\u201360%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{ElectionsVT}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Vermont''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Vermont]] was won by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[List of governors of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Bill Clinton]] of [[Arkansas]], taking 46.11% of the popular vote over incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] President [[George H. W. Bush]] of [[Texas]], who took 30.42%, a victory margin of 15.69%. [[Independent politician|Independent]] Texas billionaire [[Ross Perot]] finished in third, with 22.78% of the popular vote.<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis election would prove to be a re-aligning one for the state of Vermont. Clinton's decisive double-digit victory in the state, including a Democratic sweep of all 14 counties, represented a dramatic turnaround for a state that up to that point had been reliably Republican for over 130 years. This was only the second time in history that a Democratic presidential nominee had won Vermont's electoral votes, the first and only prior time being when [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Lyndon Johnson]] had carried the state in the [[1964 United States presidential election in Vermont|1964]] Democratic landslide. Except for 1964, Vermont had voted Republican in every presidential election from [[1856 United States presidential election in Vermont|1856]] to [[1988 United States presidential election in Vermont|1988]]. Beginning in 1992, however, Vermont instantly became a reliably Democratic state in presidential elections, voting Democratic in every election that has followed. \n\nVermont's sudden shift away from the GOP was largely a product of dramatic changes within the party itself. By the 1990s, the Republican Party, which once had a vibrant [[Progressivism|progressive]] [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] wing, began to largely consist of [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]], [[Southern United States|Southerners]], and [[Christian right|Evangelical Christians]]. Consequently, Vermont, a [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] and [[Irreligion|secular]] [[New England]] state, moved increasingly toward the Democratic Party and today is regarded as one of the safest of [[Red states and blue states|blue states]].\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Vermont<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results - Vermont|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&fips=50&f=0&off=0&elect=0&minper=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Electoral votes\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]'''\n| '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''133,592'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''46.11%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''3'''\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| [[George H. W. Bush]] ([[incumbent]])\n| align=\"right\" | 88,122\n| align=\"right\" | 30.42%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#DDDDDD; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| [[Ross Perot]]\n| align=\"right\" | 65,991\t\n| align=\"right\" | 22.78%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFCC00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Andre Marrou]]\n| align=\"right\" | 501 \t\n| align=\"right\" | 0.17%\t\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Write-ins\n| \n| align=\"right\" | 488\n| align=\"right\" | 0.17%\t\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF00FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[New Alliance Party|New Alliance]]\n| [[Lenora Fulani]]\n| align=\"right\" | 429\n| align=\"right\" | 0.15%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#ffe4e1; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Natural Law Party|Natural Law]]\n| [[John Hagelin|Dr. John Hagelin]]\n| align=\"right\" | 315\n| align=\"right\" | 0.11%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#A356DE; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Constitution Party (United States)|VT Taxpayers']]\n| [[Howard Phillips (politician)|Howard Phillips]]\n| align=\"right\" | 124\t\n| align=\"right\" | 0.04%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#c00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|Socialist Workers]]\n| [[James Warren (presidential candidate)|James Warren]]\n| align=\"right\" | 82\n| align=\"right\" | 0.03%\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800020; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[U.S. Labor Party|Democrats for Economic Recovery]]\n| [[Lyndon LaRouche]] \n| align=\"right\" | 57\n| align=\"right\" | 0.02%\t\n| align=\"right\" | 0\n|-\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\"\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''289,701'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.0%'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''3'''\n|}\n\n==Results by County==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! County\n! Clinton\n! Votes\n! Bush\n